Phase: BLUEPRINT

Objective: Upgrade the existing landing page into a deeper, more premium, more technically credible product experience with a stronger visual background system, richer content architecture, production-grade contact API handling, and advanced SEO foundations across metadata, structured data, crawlability, and performance-oriented configuration.

Step 1 – Reframe the product positioning
- Rework the landing page messaging to sound more premium, expert-level, and enterprise-ready.
- Keep all code, symbols, and comments in English while preserving all end-user visible copy in Turkish.
- Expand the page from a basic landing page into a fuller narrative: hero, trust/stats, feature architecture, process, SEO/backend credibility, contact conversion, and footer support.

Step 2 – Strengthen the global visual foundation
- Replace the current simple background with a layered visual system:
  - large radial glow layers
  - subtle grid/noise overlays
  - section separators and glow accents
  - glassmorphism surfaces that still preserve readability and contrast
- Improve `globals.css` with reusable background utility classes and smoother section rhythm.
- Ensure background effects stay performant and do not depend on heavy client-side animation libraries.

Step 3 – Establish a stronger site shell
- Upgrade `layout.tsx` metadata from placeholder-level to production-level:
  - title template
  - description
  - keywords
  - authors
  - creator/publisher
  - openGraph
  - twitter metadata
  - robots hints
  - alternates / canonical
- Add a more complete sticky header and a richer footer with service and trust cues.
- Add global providers and theme-consistent UI polish without introducing unnecessary complexity.

Step 4 – Add SEO and crawler infrastructure
- Create `robots.ts` and `sitemap.ts` routes in the App Router.
- Add `manifest.ts` for better PWA-like site metadata and richer install/share identity.
- Add structured data (JSON-LD) for the organization and service offering on the homepage.
- Add `metadataBase` and canonical handling so the app is ready for real deployment.
- Configure `next.config.ts` to remove the multi-lockfile turbopack root warning by setting the root explicitly.

Step 5 – Create a richer homepage information architecture
- Keep the hero section but make it more strategic and content-rich.
- Add at least the following sections:
  - Hero
  - Trust metrics / proof section
  - Advanced features / capability grid
  - Delivery process / workflow section
  - Technical depth section highlighting backend, SEO, performance, analytics readiness, and scalability
  - Contact / lead capture section
- Ensure each section has semantic landmarks and strong scanability.

Step 6 – Rebuild the hero to feel category-leading
- Improve headline, supporting text, CTAs, and visual proof points.
- Add stronger status cards and positioning elements showing delivery confidence, uptime, architecture, and business value.
- Preserve smooth scroll to contact and add supporting anchor navigation.
- Keep the hero responsive and visually powerful on both mobile and desktop.

Step 7 – Add credibility and trust blocks
- Build a `stats-section` or equivalent area with KPIs such as uptime, response time, launch speed, and integration coverage.
- Add short-value trust statements around architecture, security, SEO readiness, and support.
- Use reusable typed data rather than hardcoding repeated UI logic inline.

Step 8 – Expand feature storytelling
- Redesign the feature grid to speak to both product and engineering decision-makers.
- Highlight:
  - scalable architecture
  - SEO-first rendering
  - secure APIs
  - analytics and observability readiness
  - automation / AI integration
  - conversion-focused UX
- Use stronger card hierarchy and micro-copy.

Step 9 – Add a delivery/process section
- Create a section that explains how work moves from discovery to launch and optimization.
- Represent the steps visually in a timeline or step grid.
- Emphasize predictability, technical discipline, and measurable outcomes.

Step 10 – Introduce a technical excellence section
- Add a dedicated section explaining why the solution is strong in:
  - backend architecture
  - SEO
  - performance
  - security
  - scale readiness
- Make it useful for founders, marketers, and technical stakeholders at the same time.

Step 11 – Upgrade the contact form UX
- Preserve the current form but improve structure, feedback, and credibility.
- Add a hidden honeypot field for bot mitigation.
- Add better validation messaging and a clearer success response experience.
- Keep the form client-side with typed state and robust submission handling.

Step 12 – Harden the backend contact route
- Install and use `zod` for strict payload validation.
- Add server-side normalization and better error responses.
- Add lightweight in-memory rate limiting keyed by IP to reduce abuse.
- Parse forwarded IP headers safely.
- Return typed, structured JSON responses with appropriate HTTP status codes.
- Add response headers for API hardening where practical.
- Keep architecture ready for future Supabase/Firebase or email provider integration.

Step 13 – Improve code organization
- Move static marketing content into a dedicated data/config module where it improves maintainability.
- Add small reusable presentational components where they reduce duplication.
- Keep everything strictly typed and modular.

Step 14 – Performance and accessibility pass
- Keep components mostly server-rendered unless interactivity is required.
- Use client components only for interactive parts such as contact form and smooth-scroll hero actions.
- Verify headings, landmarks, labels, contrast, and focus states.
- Avoid decorative effects that hurt readability or LCP unnecessarily.

Step 15 – Validation and release readiness
- Run `npm install` for any new dependency needed by the stronger architecture.
- Run `npm run lint`.
- Run `npm run build`.
- If validation fails, read errors, fix them, and rerun until the VALIDATE phase is successful.

Step 16 – Workflow updates
- After the plan is written, transition the workflow state to `CONSTRUCT`.
- After implementation and successful validation, update `## Log`.
- Prepend a one-sentence success summary to the changelog in `project_config.md` according to RULE_SUMMARY_01.